### Melvin Rogers: Introduction
- This book is a contribution to the understanding of democracy: as an ideal and a practice.
- Persistence of racial and political inequality makes many question if democracy is up to the task of making the promises it argues to carry out.
- Ordinary people can be left to their own devices; this moral proposition is attached to debate and deliberation as we work out our problems together.
- Franchise and debate are used to guard against social and economic forces that dominate us.
- Aversion to domination, as well as franchise and debate, are central to African American political thought.
- If African Americans stressed the importance of the franchise, they also wanted to stress the centrality of democracy and the way it extends beyond the process of voting.
  - There is no way to read Morrison, Walker, or Cooper and not see that democracy is a cultural enterprise.
  - A culture of care and concern must be nurtured.
- Requires different ways of talking with each other; deployment of religious claims or display of intense emotion or marching, all of these have worked as reasons for organizing a society in one way rather than another.
  - Ways of speaking to the public.
- Invocation of the body gets at something important: the idea is that disappointment will never be permanent.
- The figures in this book put front-and-center a different level of harm exposure and disappointment.
  - Focus on forms of violence that could enter at any moment - a radical form of vulnerability as the basis for thinking about the health of democracy in the United States.
  - Focus on cultural and institutional supports by beginning with the terror of radical vulnerability.
  
