### Carol Wayne White: Anna Julie Cooper
- Cooper's politics of radical relationality: advance a type of political thinking that emphasizes interdependence as the key metaphor for envisioning the manifestations of American democratic values.
  - Notions of a democratic culture.
- Cooper was an astute philosophical thinker and an activist, an educator.
- Her writings emphasize a view of humanity that suggests we are all interdependent, there is no such thing as an isolated entity.
  - With this approach - relational ontology.
  - Cooper challenges manifestations of white supremacy.
  - Until America could actualize itself in terms of creating material conditions in which every entity in the nation could actualize itself, it would fail.
- Notion of the one and the all - she anticipates critical race theory and understands how racial distortions challenge people to see that they are the same.
- Did not have a naive universal notion of humanity, did not use evolutionary theory but suggests that we are all of the same nature and substance.
- A theme of perfectionism within a naturalized format.
- Had her foot in many different camps, she was well-read.
- Discusses fear and intentional aim to keep blacks from flourishing and actualizing themselves.
  - Heart of political thinking - America would never be America until it transforms itself into a sphere in which the all and the one are connected.

