### Michael McCann: A. Philip Randolph
- Randolph, towards the end of his life, was seen as less radical than he understood himself to be.
- We should see Randolph as consistent throughout his life.
- Why should we read him this way? What are central principles that serve as the throughline of his work?
- One of the first things that become apparent - Randolph seems to be replete with contradictions in biographies, that he holds positions and then changes them quickly.
  - Admired the Bolshevik Revolution, then becomes an anti-Communist.
  - Hostile to elites, then known as a center lobbyist and skilled negotiator with elites.
  - Wavered on his passivism; nevertheless took different positions on different wars.
  - Refused to criticize the Vietnam War, then became an activist.
- However, if we read the currents of thoughts, essays, and speeches, one sees many more consistencies and makes sense of his life.
- The most important aspect of his thought was **his focus on the relationship between capitalism and racism**.
  - Insisted there is a relationship between capitalism and racism.
  - Connection was inextricable for Randolph; capitalism as a source of racism and overcoming capitalism as inevitable to defeating racism.
- Opposed racial segregation but resisted racial integration as a primary goal - do not bring workers of capital into a hierarchal segregated economy.
- The relationship between capitalism and racism was problematic to Randolph; he insisted that capitalism was what mattered most; racism as a product of property ownership.
  - The owned status; racism as a way to divide workers and a hedge against a working class.
  - There is something to this, but it is rather simplistic.
- Pursued a class-first approach firstly; needed a mixed labor force.
  - However, did not appreciate the independent flow of white supremacist.
- Argued that the historical legacy of disenfranchisement must be viewed through the challenge, transformation, or moving beyond capitalism.
- Consistently, committed to democratic socialism.
  - There is variation in what he seemed to mean by that, but he argued that we needed democratic means and democratic socialist ends.

