### Concluding Comments

Asymmetrical attention they give to lived experiences at the expense of their ideas – knowledge of who they are supersedes their thought. There is also an issue of circularity. In the interpretation of experiences, we derived notions. Generalizing aspects of experience. Balance between the biographical and how we interpret ideas. 

Overarching narrative – the book is an antinarrative. Deal with 30 individual narratives and see which narratives emerge from them. A real emphasis on particularity of thinkers; do not box them in into an artificial framework. There are groups of chapters that emerge. 

America has fundamentally shaped race narratives. 

To write about African American contributions to modern thought is to wrestle with events, ideas, and experiences of disappointment, dread, questions about survival, and so on. A tradition of surviving and of creating; resistance is beautiful even if it means a certain type of harm. This is one of the takeaways – thinking about how we wrestle with the contours of this collected history. 

How do we create humanity? A legacy of intellectual thinking, activism that has challenged America, that makes the question of every generation ask – who are we as human beings and why are we fighting for these lofty values if not to create the notion of an expanded humanity? The spirit of essays: people struggling with their time and attempting to figure it out. 

Coalition – painful, but also intensely creative. For the time that we are in, it will take painful coalitions to fight off fascism. All of the chapters share this – at the heart of a democratic society must be a way of speaking; must truth be beautiful before you accept it? Can you accept ugliness as a condition of the transformation of society?  

